      "action": "Launch a commercial bid to secure exclusive control of the Night Courier Depot's routing ledger, leveraging the Families' liturgical charter, the \"doubly authenticated\" service's growing prestige, and the surge in gondola traffic at the Lantern-Lit Gondola Pier. Signal-House agents approach the Depot's independent operators with subsidized bandwidth leases, guaranteed message priority, and access to the Lacquer Authority's seal verification — offering a superior alternative to the Wardens' defunct permit system. The Families present the Shrine Auditors' Council with a formal petition requesting consecrated endorsement of their Depot stewardship, citing their proven track record of reliable, liturgically-protected message transit.",
      "outcome": "The Night Courier Depot's operators, many of whom lost revenue during the Wardens' chokepoint blockade, are receptive to the Families' offer. The subsidized bandwidth leases and \"doubly authenticated\" seal prestige prove persuasive — within days, a majority of independent couriers register with the Signal-House network. The routing ledger, previously maintained by a neutral consortium of operators, begins shifting toward Signal-House administrative control as more couriers adopt their cipher protocols. The Shrine Auditors' Council receives the petition favorably but delays formal endorsement, citing the need for a liturgical audit of the Depot's archives. The Families secure de facto control of the routing ledger through commercial dominance, though formal consecrated authority remains pending. The Wardens, watching from Tower Bridge Concourse, realize their counter-narrative campaign has failed to prevent the Families' expansion into the district's most critical message infrastructure.",
      "targetLocation": "Night Courier Depot",
      "tagChangeCount": 2,
      "chronicleEntryId": "d6418959-7810-42b2-aa9e-b61a6bb520da"
    }
